title: For Sale:  Walther P38 IV - Ultra Rare
postcontent: After approximately 2 million P38s were produced, Walther’s final evolution of the P38 was the P4.In the P4, Walther fixed all the idiosyncratic problems of the P38: the top cover taking flight, slide internals, fixed sight issues, manual safety either decocks too early or not at all, etc. Most noticeably the barrel was shortened by .59”, the locking block was made of a stronger material than previously and to its recess in the aluminum alloy frame was added a steel insert.The P4 is the way Walther should have designed the P38 originally, if the Wehrmacht had let them.Only 7400 P4 models were produced before all Walther P38 production ended. Virtually all went to the German Police - except for the last 451 which were imported by Interarms – designated “P38 IV” instead of P4 to differenciate as a US gun.The P38 IV pistols were shipped by Walther without a serial number on the frame (presumably German law was satisfied by the s/n on the slide). This was not discovered by Interarms until some while later, and the remaining guns were sent out to have the numbers engraved on the frame by panagraph machine. The number consequently looks very neat, and was cut through the anodizing, so the numbers are bright in the bottom.** This P38 IV is one of the group that DID NOT get receiver or barrel lettering and the s/n is on the right side of the slide only. Receiver has some small proof marks but no lettering.Walther P38 production ended in 1982, the same year as this gun. The last serial number was 607,419. This gun is 607,180.Total German P38 production …….. 2 MillionP38 P4 production............................ 7400P38 IV Imported to U.S…………….. 451P38 IV without frame markings…… unknownAll accessories included, factory test fired only. Factory target included. Taken together, each of the Tribute’s scenes inspired by Künstler’s work paints a vivid picture of life for cowboys on the frontier.

title: For Sale/Trade:  New Bills in Georgia that can make you a criminal overnight.
postcontent: Fyi Guys and Gals,  I'm sharing this info directly from Georgia's New purposed bills for the 2017 - 2018 cycle. There are two new bills on there they will vote on and we need to contact our Reps ASAP. This is a call to action (Phone Calls, Emails, letters, and word of mouth), if I could be so bold to say so.  HR 651 - Will make it illegal to own or posses a bump stock in Georgia. "There is no previsions for grandfather clause. If this bill passes, this will make you a criminal overnight if you own or posses one of these in the state of Georgia. There may be a provision later to allow you to get rid of them but you already paid for them and you wont get your money back from it. This bill is making you as a law abiding person a criminal just for owing something and they will send you to jail for 5 years if you do. " HB 11 - Will make it mandatory that each person who carries a gun in obtain a weapons permit and have to go through a licensed weapons safety class. $30 for the permit and unknown fee for the class. " this is another tax/ Fee for the Right to Bear Arms. This would mean everyone who isn't in the military or law enforcement would have to pay to go to a class in order to carry in the state of Georgia. If everyone has to go how long of delay would it be to get into a class? Ever hear of supply and demand? We should not have to pay a fee or a tax to exercise a right or have to pay someone to go to a class in order to pay for a right. We do not have to pay for any of the other rights, so why do we have to pay for this? It's just another way to limit the "Free Exercise there of" of the people while masking as a protection of our security and freedom."  We all need to contact out state reps as individual voters and express our concerns to them.
